My thought was to get the original report up and running so that it would be modified with the SAP support packages going forward. Any combination of shipments or deliveries can be combined onto the same load as long as they are referencing the same carrier number. Pick list numbers and could have been, and probably should have been, combined onto one shipment as they had the same shipment specification number, which meant that all infomration in the VASPEZ table was the same between the two pick lists. VSS did allow it to go on the same load since all pick lists were referencing the same carrier Hi John, the question is why shouldn't we. I checked the shipments and there is no reason to deny putting them in one load. A load is principally just a carrier. You put the packages on a carrier but you don't know how far it drives. For example If you make a load for three customers, the carrier can drive to a HUB and the divide it in three different carriers. Therefore it is allowed to put them together. Group policy was not being applied to the machine and further investigation showed that no network resources were accessible. No UNC paths, no DFS paths, nothing. Machine was accessible on the network, able to resolve and ping network resources but simply unable to connect to the resources. Event log showed that the TCP IP NetBIOS Helper service was unable to start. Looking at the services on the machine, the service was listed but the description couldn't be found so this appeared to be the root of the problem. Uninstalled Client for Microsoft Networks from the NIC, rebooted PC, and the TCP IP NetBIOS service was properly removed. Reinstalled the client for MS networks on the NIC but the service wasn't returned. Further investigation showed that the lmhsvc.dll file in the system directory appeared to be corrupt information on the details tab of this file were missing. This file was copied from a working machine but service still didn't appear after a reboot. To restore the service, the HKEY LOCAL MACHINEkey was copied from a known working machine and imported to After rebooting the service was running properly. PROBLEM DESCRIPTION Txn COGI was timing out when user execute it with following two values Planning Plant Production Supervisor PROBLEM CAUSE Within Txn COGI, the record selection needs a value in one of the five selection fields at the top, viz, Plant, Storage Location, Material, MRP Controller, Error Record, or a value in field Order. All other selection fields just acts as additional filters, but they alone cannot select the error records without having a value in one of the above fields. Note field Production Supervisor is a filter, but it is also made a part of record selection so specifying ProductionSupervisor helps execution speed. PROBLEM SOLUTION Put value in the field Plant instead of Planning Plant. PROBLEM WORKAROUND None.
